context: Lancashire has a long and highly productive tradition of <a2_0>music making<a2_0/>. In the early modern era the county shared in the national tradition of <a3_0>balladry<a3_0/>, including perhaps the finest border ballad, "<a4_0>The Ballad of Chevy Chase<a4_0/>", thought to have been composed by the <a1_0>Lancashire<a1_0/>-born minstrel <a0_0><b6_0>Richard Sheale<b6_0/><a0_0/>. The county was also a common location for folk songs, including <b5_0>"The Lancashire Miller"<b5_0/>, "Warrington Ale" and "The soldier's farewell to Manchester", while Liverpool, as a major seaport, was the subject of many sea shanties, including "The Leaving of Liverpool" and <b7_0>"Maggie May"<b7_0/>, beside several local Wassailing songs. In the Industrial Revolution changing social and economic patterns helped create new traditions and styles of folk song, often linked to <b8_0>migration<b8_0/> and patterns of work. These included processional dances, often associated with rushbearing or the Wakes Week festivities, and types of step dance, most famously <b9_0>clog dancing<b9_0/>.
